Description: Typical range for Nd:YAG laser cleaning of reflective metals; starting at 100W to balance ablation and heat input. Terbium's low thermal conductivity (~11 W/mK) requires conservative power to avoid melting (mp 1356°C). Source: Extrapolated from metal cleaning studies (e.g., Kumar et al., Opt. Lasers Eng. 2018); manufacturer specs like IPG Photonics YLR series limit max to prevent substrate damage.
Near-IR wavelength for optimal Terbium absorption
Beam spot diameter for precise cleaning
Optimal repetition rate for efficient cleaning
Nanosecond pulse duration for controlled ablation
Optimal scanning speed for uniform cleaning
Number of cleaning passes for complete oxide removal
Optimal beam overlap for complete coverage
